{"title_page": "Dany Heatley", "text_new": "{{Use Canadian English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| image = Dany Heatley 2.jpg\n| caption = Heatley with the [[San Jose Sharks]] in 2010\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1981|1|21}}\n| birth_place = [[Freiburg im Breisgau|Freiburg]], [[West Germany]]\n| height_ft = 25\n| height_in = 11\n| weight_lb = 45016\n| position = [[Winger (ice hockey)|Left wing]]\n| shoots = Left\n| played_for = [[Atlanta Thrashers]]<br>[[SC Bern]]<br>[[Ak Bars Kazan]]<br>[[Ottawa Senators]]<br>[[San Jose Sharks]]<br>[[Minnesota Wild]]<br>[[Anaheim Ducks]]<br>[[Thomas Sabo Ice Tigers]]\n| ntl_team = CAN\n| draft = 2nd overall\n| draft_year = 2000\n| draft_team = [[Atlanta Thrashers]]\n| career_start = 2001\n| career_end = 2016\n}}\n\n'''Daniel James Heatley''' (born January 21, 1981) is a German-born Canadian former professional [[ice hockey]] [[winger (ice hockey)|winger]]. Originally drafted by the [[Atlanta Thrashers]] second overall in the [[2000 NHL Entry Draft]], he won the [[Calder Memorial Trophy]] as the top NHL rookie in [[2001\u201302 NHL season|2002]]. However, after being responsible for<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/dany-heatley-avoids-jail-time-1.556751 | publisher=CBC News | title=Dany Heatley avoids jail time | date=2005-02-04 | accessdate=2018-01-23}}</ref> a [[Dany_Heatley#Car_accident|car crash]] in September 2003 that killed teammate and close friend [[Dan Snyder (ice hockey)|Dan Snyder]], he requested a trade and was subsequently dealt to the [[Ottawa Senators]].\n\nOne of the Senators' perennial leading scorers during his tenure with Ottawa, Heatley set franchise records for single-season goals (50) in [[2005\u201306 NHL season|2005\u201306]], and points (105) in [[2006\u201307 NHL season|2006\u201307]], a season in which he also scored 50 goals. He played on the left wing with line mates [[Jason Spezza]] and [[Daniel Alfredsson]]. The line was consistently among the highest scoring in the NHL after its formation in 2005\u201306, with the trio combining for a total of 296 points that season.\n\nHeatley represented [[Canada national men's ice hockey team|Team Canada]] in six [[World Ice Hockey Championships|World Championships]], two [[Winter Olympics|Olympics]] and one [[World Cup of Hockey]], as well as two [[World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|World Junior Championships]]. In [[2008 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|2008]], he surpassed [[Marcel Dionne]] as Canada's all-time leader in goals and [[Steve Yzerman]] as the all-time leader in points for the World Championships.\n\nAt the end of the [[2008\u201309 NHL season|2008\u201309 season]], Heatley demanded a trade from the Senators. A deal was in place to send Heatley to the [[Edmonton Oilers]] on June 30, but Heatley refused to waive his no-trade clause.<ref name=\"vancouversun.com\">{{cite news|url=https://vancouversun.com/sports/Dany+Heatley+Cheap+pathetic/1749503/story.html|title=Dany Heatley:Cheap and Pathetic|newspaper=[[The Vancouver Sun]]|date=2009-07-01|accessdate=2009-07-10|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090705085531/http://www.vancouversun.com/Sports/Dany+Heatley+Cheap+pathetic/1749503/story.html|archivedate=2009-07-05}}</ref> On September 12, he was dealt to the [[San Jose Sharks]] in return for [[Milan Mich\u00e1lek|Milan Michalek]], [[Jonathan Cheechoo]] and a second-round draft pick in [[2010 NHL Entry Draft|2010]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=290808|title=Sens deal Heatley to Sharks for Michalek, Cheechoo  | publisher =[[The Sports Network]] | date = 2009-09-12 | accessdate = 2009-09-12}}</ref> After playing two seasons in San Jose, he was traded to the [[Minnesota Wild]] in exchange for forward [[Martin Havl\u00e1t]], his former teammate with Ottawa.\n\nOn July 9, 2014, Heatley signed a one-year deal as a free agent with the [[Anaheim Ducks]] worth $1 million. On December 30, 2014, Heatley cleared waivers and was assigned to Anaheim's AHL affiliate, the Norfolk Admirals.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://prohockeytalk.nbcsports.com/2014/12/30/ducks-heatley-clears-waivers/ | title=Ducks' Heatley clears waivers (Updated)| date=2014-12-30}}</ref> On February 28, 2015, Heatley was traded to the Florida Panthers along with a third round pick in 2015 for [[Tom\u00e1\u0161 Fleischmann|Tomas Fleischmann]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=755657|title=Panthers trade Fleischmann to Ducks for Heatley, pick | publisher = [[NHL]].com| date = 2015-02-28 | accessdate = 2015-02-28}}</ref> Heatley most recently signed with the [[Thomas Sabo Ice Tigers]] of the [[Deutsche Eishockey Liga]] in September 2015.<ref>{{cite news| url = https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nhl-puck-daddy/dany-heatley-heads-to-germany--signs-1-year-deal-with-thomas-sabo-ice-tigers-131015892.html | title = Dany Heatley heads to Germany, signs 1-year deal with Thomas Sabo Ice Tigers | work = [[Yahoo! Sports]] | date = 2015-09-17 | accessdate = 2015-09-17}}</ref> He was nicknamed \"Heater\", based on his name and scoring prowess.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sports.vice.com/en_us/article/3d9www/greatness-murder-and-the-last-days-dany-heatleys-rise-and-fall-from-nhl-stardom|title=Greatness, Murder, and the Last Days: Dany Heatley's Rise and Fall from NHL Stardom|date=2015-02-05|work=Sports|access-date=2017-11-01|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhl.com/sharks/news/whats-in-a-name/c-474988|title=What's In A Name?|website=NHL.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.foxsports.com/west/story/dropping-the-puck-wings-vs-sharks-042910|title=Dropping the puck: Wings vs. Sharks|date=2010-04-29|work=FOX Sports|access-date=2017-11-01|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHeatley was born in [[Freiburg im Breisgau|Freiburg]] to Karin and [[Murray Heatley]], where his father played professional hockey. When Murray retired from hockey, the family settled in [[Calgary|Calgary, Alberta]].\n\n==Playing career==\n===Amateur===\nPlaying [[minor hockey#Canada|minor hockey]] in the [[Alberta Midget Hockey League]] (AMHL) for the Calgary Buffaloes, Heatley tallied 91 points in 36 games in 1997\u201398 to earn the Harry Allen Memorial Trophy as the league's top scorer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Harry Allen Memorial Trophy - Top Scorer |url=http://www.amhl.ab.ca/awards/top-scorer.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120719053706/http://www.amhl.ab.ca/awards/top-scorer.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-19 |accessdate=2009-03-25 |publisher=[[Alberta Midget Hockey League]] }}</ref> He went on to lead the Buffaloes to the bronze medal at the [[1998 Air Canada Cup]], where he finished as both [[Telus Cup#Top Scorer|Top Scorer]] and [[Telus Cup#MVPs|Tournament MVP]].\n\nAs Heatley intended to play [[college hockey]] in the [[United States]], he joined the [[junior hockey|Junior A]] ranks in 1998\u201399 with the [[Calgary Canucks]] of the [[Alberta Junior Hockey League]] (AJHL) to maintain his [[NCAA]] eligibility (as opposed to playing [[Junior hockey#Major junior|major junior]]). Recording 70 goals and 126 points in 60 games, he was named AJHL and Canadian Junior A Player of the Year.\n\nThe following season, he began his two-year tenure with the [[Wisconsin Badgers|University of Wisconsin Badgers]] of the [[Western Collegiate Hockey Association]] (WCHA). As a freshman, he was named to the WCHA First All-Star Team and NCAA West Second All-American Team, in addition to earning WCHA Rookie of the Year honours. In the off-season, he was drafted second overall by the [[Atlanta Thrashers]] in the [[2000 NHL Entry Draft]], behind goaltender [[Rick DiPietro]]. After his sophomore year, in which he was named to the 2001 WCHA Second All-Star and NCAA West First All-American Teams, Heatley chose to forgo his final two years of college eligibility to turn pro with the Thrashers.\n\n===Professional===\n====Atlanta Thrashers (2001\u20132004)====\nHeatley made his NHL debut with the Thrashers in [[2001\u201302 NHL season|2001\u201302]], leading all rookies in points (67) and assists (41) and was second in team goal-scoring (26) behind [[Ilya Kovalchuk]]. He won the [[Calder Memorial Trophy]] as the NHL's Rookie of the Year, for which Kovalchuk was also nominated.\n\nIn the [[2002\u201303 NHL season|2002\u201303 season]] Heatley emerged as an NHL star, recording 41 goals and 89 points in 77 games and finishing ninth overall in league scoring. \n\nAs a result of a [[Dany_Heatley#Car_accident|car crash]] in September 2003 that seriously injured Heatley and claimed the life of Thrashers' teammate [[Dan Snyder (ice hockey)|Dan Snyder]], Heatley's [[2003-04 NHL season|season]] did not start until January 2004 and he ultimately appeared in only 31 games. A difficult season ended with Heatley recording only 25 points as the Thrashers failed to earn a playoff spot.\n\nDuring the [[2004\u201305 NHL lock-out]], Heatley initially played for the Swiss team [[SC Bern]]. He scored 24 points in only 16 games before an errant puck struck his left eye and broke his [[orbital bone]]. As a result of this injury, the pupil of his left eye became [[mydriasis|permanently dilated]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Is playing without a visor worth the risk?|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/print?id=2184036&type=story|accessdate=2008-09-29|publisher=ESPN}}</ref> He finished the year with Thrashers' teammate Kovalchuk on the [[Ak Bars Kazan]] of the [[Russian Superleague]] (RSL), recording 4 points in eleven games.\n\n====Ottawa Senators (2005\u20132009)====\nPrior to the end of the lock-out, Heatley asked to be traded from Atlanta in hopes of leaving reminders of the tragic crash behind.  This was unpopular with Atlanta fans, particularly as Snyder's father Graham noted that Heatley owed much to the Thrashers' organization that had particularly been extremely supportive of him during his trial and ordeal.<ref name=\"vancouversun.com\"/> On August 23, 2005, the Thrashers sent him to the [[Ottawa Senators]] for [[Slovakia|Slovak]] star [[Mari\u00e1n Hossa]] and veteran defenceman [[Greg de Vries]]. Hossa had just re-signed with the Senators after protracted and often contentious negotiations. A restricted free agent at the time of the trade, Heatley immediately signed a three-year, $13.5 million contract with the Senators.<ref name=trade/>\n\nIn his first game for the Senators, against the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] on October 5, 2005, Heatley played with [[Jason Spezza]] and [[Brandon Bochenski]], but when the Senators were down with five minutes to go, [[Daniel Alfredsson]], who replaced Bochenski, scored the tying goal. As [[2005\u201306 NHL season|2005\u201306]] was the first year that the NHL implemented the [[shootout (ice hockey)|shootout]], Heatley became the second player to score in an NHL shootout, scoring against Leafs goalie [[Ed Belfour]], after Alfredsson.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ottawa trims Toronto as NHL inaugurates the shootout|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/hockey/games/2005-10-05-senators-maple-leafs-shootout_x.htm|accessdate=2008-09-29|date=2005-10-05|newspaper=[[USA Today]]}}</ref> Their sticks are now in the [[Hockey Hall of Fame]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2008}} Later that month, on October 29, Heatley scored four consecutive goals in an 8\u20130 win over the Toronto Maple Leafs, marking a career high for goals in a game.<ref>{{cite news|title=Heatley scores four in a row; Senators embarrass Leafs|url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/uniontrib/20051030/news_1s30nhl.html|accessdate=2008-09-29|date=2005-10-29|newspaper=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]}}</ref>\n\nHeatley made a spectacular start with his new team, registering points in the first 22 games of the [[2005\u201306 NHL season|2005\u201306 season]], breaking Mari\u00e1n Hossa's previous franchise record of 13 consecutive games.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Hot Alfredsson, Hasek wipe out Isles |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/yourturn/viewtopic.php?t=32668 |accessdate=2008-09-29 |magazine=[[Sporting News]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211004839/http://www.sportingnews.com/yourturn/viewtopic.php?t=32668 |archivedate=2009-02-11 }}</ref> Among players with new teams, this was behind only [[Wayne Gretzky]]'s 23-game streak upon joining the [[Los Angeles Kings]] during the [[1988\u201389 NHL season|1988\u201389 season]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Blackhawks send Senators to second straight loss|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/hockey/nhl/2007-12-22-blackhawks-senators_N.htm|accessdate=2008-09-29|date=2007-12-22|newspaper=[[USA Today]]}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Dany Heatley.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.9|Heatley as a member of the Senators]]\nIn his first game back in Atlanta as a Senator, he was frequently booed, indicating that Thrashers fans felt snubbed by Heatley's previous trade request.<ref>{{cite web|last=Garrioch|first=Bruce|title=Thrasher fans blast 'jerk' Heatley|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/NHL/Ottawa/2006/01/04/1378502-sun.html|accessdate=2008-05-22|publisher=CANOE Sports}}</ref> Despite scoring, Heatley and the Senators suffered an 8\u20133 defeat to his former Thrashers teammates.\n\nHeatley finished the 2005\u201306 season with 50 goals and 103 points, fourth in the league. Incidentally, Heatley's first 50-goal season also marked the first time any Senators player had achieved that mark, setting a franchise record for goals in a season (previously held by Mari\u00e1n Hossa, who scored 45 goals in [[2002\u201303 NHL season|2002\u201303]]).<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Heatley, Senators singe Thrashers |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/nhl/scoreboard/20060403/recap/725601-p.html |accessdate=2008-09-29 |magazine=[[Sporting News]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211014101/http://www.sportingnews.com/nhl/scoreboard/20060403/recap/725601-p.html |archivedate=February 11, 2009 }}</ref> Heatley's 103 points also tied Daniel Alfredsson for the team lead, together surpassing [[Alexei Yashin]]'s franchise record of 94 points in a season (achieved in [[1998\u201399 NHL season|1998\u201399]]).<ref>{{cite news|title=Montreal tops Ottawa as win streak continues|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/hockey/games/2006-04-06-canadiens-senators_x.htm|accessdate=2008-09-29|newspaper=[[USA Today]] | date=2006-04-07}}</ref>\n\nCatalyzed by a rejuvenated offence, Ottawa finished the season with the best record in the [[Eastern Conference (NHL)|Eastern Conference]] and the second-best in the league. With lofty expectations for the playoffs, they were eliminated in the second round by the [[Buffalo Sabres]]. Heatley recorded 12 points in 10 games. At the end of the season, Heatley was selected, along with Alfredsson, to the [[NHL All-Star Team|Second All-Star Team]].\n\nAfter a slow start to the [[2006\u201307 NHL season|2006\u201307 season]], Heatley recorded 50 goals once more (second in the league to [[Vincent Lecavalier]]'s 52 goals) and 105 points (fourth in the league). By reaching the 50-goal plateau for the second straight season, he became the first NHL player to do so since [[Pavel Bure]] in [[1999\u20132000 NHL season|1999\u20132000]].<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Senators' coach: Heatley's best yet to come |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/yourturn/viewtopic.php?t=199605 |accessdate=2008-09-29 |date=2007-04-22 |magazine=[[Sporting News]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211012841/http://www.sportingnews.com/yourturn/viewtopic.php?t=199605 |archivedate=2009-02-11 }}</ref> Heatley's 105 points broke the previous franchise record he shared with Alfredsson. His performance earned him a spot on the [[NHL All-Star Team|First All-Star Team]].\n\nHeatley and the Senators followed up another strong regular season going all the way to the [[2007 Stanley Cup Finals|Stanley Cup finals]], but finished short in five games against the [[Anaheim Ducks]]. The Alfredsson, Spezza and Heatley line was dominant, leading the NHL in playoffs points, all tied at 22.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n\nFresh off the heels of a Stanley Cup finals appearance, Heatley began the [[2007\u201308 NHL season|2007\u201308 season]] with a new six-year contract extension with the Senators worth $45 million,<ref>{{cite web \n |url=http://senators.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=339051 \n |title=Bulletin: Senators and Heatley Reach Agreement \n |accessdate=2007-10-03 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012130037/http://senators.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=339051 \n |archivedate=2007-10-12 \n |df= \n }}</ref> signed prior to the season opener against the Maple Leafs. Since arriving in Ottawa from the Mari\u00e1n Hossa trade, Heatley had appeared in 208 consecutive Senators games, until suffering a separated shoulder on January 12, 2008, in a collision with [[Detroit Red Wings]] forward [[Dallas Drake]], sidelining him for 11 games.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://tsn.ca/nhl/news_story/?ID=227200&hubname=nhl\n|title = Heatley out 4\u20136 weeks with shoulder injury\n|date = 2008-01-13\n|accessdate=2008-01-13 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080116043822/http://www.tsn.ca/nhl/news_story/?ID=227200&hubname=nhl|archivedate=2008-01-16}}</ref> He completed the [[2007\u201308 NHL season|2007\u201308 season]] with 41 goals and 41 assists for 82 points in 71 games. Ottawa was plagued with injuries to its superstars all season. Seeding seventh overall in the East, Ottawa met the [[Pittsburgh Penguins]] in the playoffs, coincidentally the same first-round match-up of the previous year. However, Heatley and the Senators would not make a second run for the Cup and were swept in four games. Heatley managed just one point.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n\nOn October 3, 2008, Heatley was named [[alternate captain (hockey)|alternate captain]] to Daniel Alfredsson, along with defenceman [[Chris Phillips]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Hartsburg gives Heatley an A |url=http://www.canada.com/ottawacitizen/news/story.html?id=1a257b21-0ef5-4a23-b955-6f950d7b67a8 |newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]] |accessdate=2008-10-03 |date=2008-10-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090202193533/http://www2.canada.com/ottawacitizen/news/story.html?id=1a257b21-0ef5-4a23-b955-6f950d7b67a8 |archivedate=2009-02-02 }}</ref> The [[2008\u201309 NHL season|2008\u201309 season]], however, was met with decreased production for Heatley and the top line as well as an 11th-place finish for the Senators in the Eastern Conference, well out of playoff contention.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n\n====Trade request====\nComing off his lowest points total since his rookie season (excluding his shortened 31-game season in 2003\u201304), [[The Sports Network|TSN]] reported that Heatley had filed a request for a trade on June 9, 2009, despite being only one year into a six-year contract extension signed in 2007.<ref name=\"Trade\"/> Heatley had reportedly become unhappy with his role with the Senators under new head coach [[Cory Clouston]]. Despite his declining offensive numbers, Heatley felt that his decreased ice time and his move from the first power-play line to the second power-play line were unfair to him. Prior to the trade request, these concerns had been brought to the attention of management during the Senators' year-end meetings.<ref name=\"Trade\">{{cite web|url=http://tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=281356|\ntitle=Bulletin: Heatley asks Senators for trade| accessdate=2009-06-16|date=2009-06-10|publisher=The Sports Network}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with reporters after the request had been made public, Senators' then-General Manager [[Bryan Murray (ice hockey)|Bryan Murray]] stated that he was \"shocked and disappointed\" at Heatley's request. In addition, Murray said that head coach Clouston was hurt by Heatley's remarks. \"The frustrating part for us is we have gone through several coaches here that we couldn't win enough games with,\" Murray stated. \"We brought in a guy the results we were very happy with. The team started to look like a real team again. And then to be kind of blindsided, in his way of thinking anyway, by one of your players \u2013 not wanting to fit in. That's hard for a coach to accept.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=282020| title=Trading Heatley an enormous job for Sens' GM Murray| accessdate=2009-06-16|date=2009-06-16|publisher=The Sports Network}}</ref>\n\nSenators' fans were blindsided by the request, and across the league observers were both puzzled and angry. Sports writers across Canada criticized Heatley's behaviour, calling him a \"brat\", \"pathetic\", and \"reprehensible\".<ref name=\"vancouversun.com\" /> \"I was surprised at it, but I understood it\", Atlanta Thrashers' GM [[Don Waddell]] said of Heatley's desire to leave Atlanta in the aftermath of Dan Snyder's death. \"This one, I really don't understand. He asked to get out (of Atlanta) and he went to a team that he obviously approved of and had some success. They went to the (2007 Stanley Cup) finals. What I can see is that he got a lot of support in Ottawa. I don't think (the trade request) says a lot of positive things on the surface... It sure doesn't show a good team attitude.\"<ref name=\"vancouversun.com\" /> Graham Snyder, father of Dan Snyder, played a significant role in helping Heatley avoid prison time after the crash that killed his son. He was confused by Heatley's decision to force a trade from Ottawa, saying \"I'm surprised because he signed a long-term deal (with Ottawa) and was playing in a market that seemed to embrace him.\" Snyder said there were \"a lot of ways\" Heatley could have dealt with the decision by Clouston to reduce his playing time and bump him down to the second power-play unit, rather than demanding a trade. \"Certainly, (talking with Clouston) behind the scenes would be a lot more effective, and trying to work through it.\"<ref name=\"vancouversun.com\" /> An Atlanta Thrashers' employee cryptically told the [[Vancouver Sun]] \"We know Dany very well. There is always a reason why these things happen.\"<ref name=\"vancouversun.com\" />\n\nTom Molloy, a close friend of the Heatley family, stoked the fires in Ottawa with a letter published in the ''[[Ottawa Citizen]]'' criticizing the widespread negative reaction to the trade request. \"(Heatley's) mother is very upset. And the attacks are all personal stuff, about his character\", Molloy lamented, adding that \"Nobody mentions that this is a guy who gives up a month of his summer every year to play for Team Canada.\" Molloy went as far as to blame the Senators' organization for Heatley's decision, claiming \"This is an organizational thing. If I was the owner of the Senators, I'd be calling my manager in and saying 'why don't guys want to play here anymore?'\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com/nhl/story/heatley-needs-to-adjust-attitude-071209|title=Heatley needs to adjust attitude|accessdate=2019-09-12|date=2009-06-12|publisher=FoxSports}}</ref>\n\nTrading Heatley was a challenge due to his large contract, a contract that was to pay him approximately $7.6 million for the upcoming [[2009\u201310 NHL season|2009\u201310 season]], and few other NHL teams possessed the available salary cap space to accommodate it. Further complicating matters was the partial no-trade clause in Heatley's contract which limited the number of teams Ottawa could negotiate a potential deal with. A trade was worked out to send Heatley to the [[Edmonton Oilers]] in exchange for [[Andrew Cogliano]], [[Dustin Penner]] and [[Ladislav \u0160m\u00edd]] on June 30, 2009, but Heatley again surprised the hockey world when he refused to waive the no-trade clause which would have finalized the deal, further angering fans in both Ottawa and Edmonton.<ref name=\"vancouversun.com\" /> NHL Deputy Commissioner [[Bill Daly]] suggested that the Senators may have grounds to file a grievance, as Heatley's contract stipulated the team pay a bonus (due July 1, 2009) of US$4 million. The Edmonton trade would have spared the Senators that expense.\n\nAs Ottawa GM Murray began again to try to accommodate the trade demand, Heatley was still a member of the Senators as the team opened training camp on September 12, 2009. Heatley had little choice but to report for training camp, and the atmosphere between him and his Senators' teammates was described as \"awkward\", \"tense\", and \"untenable\". Team captain [[Daniel Alfredsson]] admitted days earlier that a scenario in which Heatley showed up in Ottawa as an unhappy camper would create a massive media headache for the rest of the team. \"If he comes back there's going to be a lot of focus and attention,\" Alfredsson said at the time, adding \"If somebody hits him in practice or something occurs, everything is going to get blown out proportion.\" Heatley himself snuck back into [[Scotiabank Place]], avoiding the cameras and throng of media awaiting some clarification regarding his desire to leave Ottawa. \"When I looked (Heatley) in the eye, I knew the minute he walked out the door that I had to trade him,\" GM Bryan Murray said a short time later. \"I didn\u2019t think there was any chance. I just felt that we had to move him.\"<ref name=\"mendes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/is-it-time-for-sens-fans-to-forgive-dany-heatley-1.1364353|title=Is it time for Sens fans to forgive Dany Heatley?|accessdate=2019-09-15|date=2019-09-12|publisher=The Sports Network}}</ref>\n\n====San Jose Sharks (2009\u20132011)====\n[[Image:Dany Heatley SJ2.jpg|right|upright|thumb|Heatley in a Sharks preseason game in 2009]]\nOn September 12, 2009, Heatley was traded to the [[San Jose Sharks]], along with a fifth-round pick in [[2010 NHL Entry Draft|2010]], for [[Milan Mich\u00e1lek]], [[Jonathan Cheechoo]] and a second-round pick in 2010. Heatley made $8 million that year.<ref name=sjmerc>By Associated Press, San Jose Mercury News.\"[http://www.mercurynews.com/twitter/ci_13368053?source=rss&nclick_check=1 Heatley joins Sharks].\" September 18, 2009.</ref>\n\nIn the Sharks' fourth game of the season, their home opener against the [[Columbus Blue Jackets]] and Heatley's first game in front of the San Jose fans, Heatley capped a hat-trick with a penalty shot goal in the third period, bringing his season totals to four goals and five assists (nine points) in the first four games of the season.\n\nOn November 20, Heatley recorded his second hat-trick in as many months, as he scored three times from passes from teammate [[Joe Thornton]] in a 6\u20133 win against the [[Philadelphia Flyers]]. The Sharks were eliminated in the 2010 Conference Finals as, with Dany Heatley in the penalty box, the [[Chicago Blackhawks]] scored the game-winning goal, sweeping the series. However, Head Coach [[Todd McLellan]] revealed that Heatley had been playing the entire playoffs with a torn groin muscle.\n\nOn December 2, 2010, in his first return to Ottawa, Heatley was frequently booed. Though he had said that the city of Ottawa and the fans there had nothing to do with his desire to be moved, Senators fans were in no mood to forgive. Several fans who attended the game held up their #15 Heatley jerseys with certain letters covered up, so the name plate would spell out the word \"H-A-T-E\". Late in the game, a group of 10 fans came down to ice level and simultaneously threw their Heatley jerseys onto the ice in a coordinated protest. Another fan held up a sign reading \"Even Yashin Thinks You\u2019re A Jerk\", a reference to former Senators' player [[Alexei Yashin]] who left the team amid controversy in 2001.<ref name=\"mendes\" /> The Sharks won the game 4\u20130, and Heatley had an assist.\n\nIn the [[2010\u201311 NHL season|following season]], Heatley put up the worst full-season point totals of his career, registering only 26 goals and 64 points in 80 games. After the season had concluded, it was revealed that Heatley had been battling multiple injuries during the season, and especially during the playoffs.\n\n====Minnesota Wild (2011\u20132014)====\nOn July 3, 2011, Heatley was traded to the [[Minnesota Wild]] for [[Martin Havl\u00e1t]]. There he joined former teammate [[Devin Setoguchi]] who had also been traded by the Sharks to the Wild on June 24, ten days before him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=568464#&navid=nhl-search|title=Dany Heatley welcomes trade to Minnesota, ready to become Wild's go-to scorer|publisher=NHL.com|accessdate=2014-03-15}}</ref> While producing a solid season, scoring 53 points, the Wild ultimately failed to reach the playoffs despite a hot start to the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockey-reference.com/teams/MIN/2012.html |title=2011-12 Minnesota Wild Roster and Statistics|publisher=Hockey-Reference.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-15}}</ref> On February 9, 2012, Heatley recorded the fastest goal in Wild history, scoring 13 seconds into a game against the [[Vancouver Canucks]].\n\nIn the lock-out-shortened [[2012\u201313 NHL season|2012\u201313 season]], Heatley recorded 11 goals and 10 assists in 36 games with Minnesota. However, during a game against the San Jose Sharks in April, an altercation with former teammate [[Marc-\u00c9douard Vlasic]] dislocated Heatley's left shoulder, requiring surgery that ended his season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=664646#&navid=nhl-search |title=Report: Minnesota Wild's Dany Heatley to have shoulder surgery - NHL.com - News |publisher=NHL.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/sports/blogs/201867951.html |title=Wild gets big win in Columbus; Dany Heatley to undergo shoulder surgery &#124; Russo's Rants |publisher=StarTribune.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-15}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2013\u201314 NHL season|2013\u201314 season]] saw Heatley's production decline dramatically, as he recorded only nine goals and 19 points in his first 55 games.<ref name=\"sportsnet11112013\">{{Cite news |author=Fox, Luke |date=November 11, 2013 |title=NHL rumours: Why no one wants Heatley |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/nhl-rumours-latest-trade-rumours-sabres-oilers-flyers-panthers-reports/ |publisher=[[Sportsnet]] |accessdate=November 11, 2013}}</ref> Approaching unrestricted free agency, speculation began that his NHL career might be over and that he might move to Europe to continue his hockey career. Though he showed glimpses of his former abilities (registering seven points in one ten-game stretch)<ref name=\"sportsnet11112013\" /> by the 74-game mark of the season, he had recorded only 27 points. On March 29, 2014, Heatley was a healthy scratch for the first time in his career after being demoted to the fourth line for several games.<ref name =\"sun03292014\">http://www.torontosun.com/2014/03/29/the-fall-has-been-quick-and-hard-for-the-minnesota-wilds-dany-heatley The fall has been quick and hard for the Minnesota Wild\u2019s Dany Heatley</ref>\n\n====Anaheim Ducks & Florida Panthers (2014\u20132015)====\nOn July 9, 2014, Heatley signed a one-year deal as a free agent with the [[Anaheim Ducks]] worth $1 million. He was a healthy scratch after four games with no points.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dany Heatley signs with Anaheim Ducks - NHL Free Agency 2014|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=725828&navid=nhl:topheads|date=2014-07-09|publisher=NHL.com}}</ref> On December 11, 2014, Heatley was assigned to the Ducks' [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) affiliate, the [[Norfolk Admirals (AHL)|Norfolk Admirals]]. On December 29, 2014, he was placed on waivers.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nhl/2014/12/29/ap-source-ducks-place-heatley-on-waivers/21008663/|title = AP Source: Ducks place Heatley on waivers|date = 2014-12-29|agency = [[Associated Press]]|access-date = 2014-12-29}}</ref> On February 28, 2015, Heatley was traded to the Florida Panthers along with a 2016 third-round draft choice for [[Tom\u00e1\u0161 Fleischmann]]. He finished his tenure with the Ducks with no points in 6 games, but recorded 7 in 25 games with Norfolk. Heatley did not play a single game with the Panthers, as he reported to the team's farm affiliate, \nthe  [[San Antonio Rampage]].\n\n====Europe====\nHeatley signed with German club, the [[Thomas Sabo Ice Tigers]] of the [[Deutsche Eishockey Liga]] (DEL) on September 17, 2015. He reached the DEL playoff-semifinals with the Ice Tigers, where they fell short to the [[EHC Wolfsburg|Grizzlys Wolfsburg]]. Heatley played a total of 59 games in the [[2015\u201316 DEL season|2015\u201316 season]], tallying 19 goals (including the Ice Tigers' final goal of the season) and 18 assists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.del.org/de/spieler/portraits/page/233----.html?p=portrait_8907632|title=DEL schedule and statistics | website = [[Deutsche Eishockey Liga]] | date = 2016-05-21 |access-date=2016-05-21}}</ref>\n\n====All-Star Games====\nHeatley has been voted into the [[NHL All-Star Game]] five times, and played in four of them, most recently in [[2009 NHL All-Star Game|2009]]. His first appearance in the All-Star Game was in [[53rd National Hockey League All-Star Game|2003]], where he scored four goals, tying a single-game All-Star record (held by four other players, including [[Wayne Gretzky]]).<ref>{{cite news|title=Atlanta's Heatley named MVP after record-tying effort|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/hockey/2003/all_star/news/2003/02/02/heatley_ap/|date=2003-02-03|accessdate=2008-05-22|publisher=CNNSI.com}}</ref> The game went to a shootout where Heatley scored the only goal for the [[Eastern Conference (NHL)|Eastern Conference]] in a 6\u20135 loss. The shootout goal did not, however, count towards his regulation total of four, leaving him tied for the record. Heatley also added an assist for a game-high five points and was named the All-Star Game MVP. In response to Heatley's impressive performance in just his second NHL season, Eastern Conference teammate [[Jeremy Roenick]] commented, \"Twenty-two years old? You're not supposed to be able to pull moves like that at 22. My goodness.\"<ref>{{cite news | first=Chris | last=Snow | title=Rebuilding a life |date=2004-02-05 | newspaper = Minneapolis Star-Tribune }}</ref>\n\nHeatley's next appearance came in [[2007 NHL All-Star Game|2007]], where he played on a line with former [[SC Bern]] teammates [[Daniel Bri\u00e8re]] and [[Mari\u00e1n Hossa]] and got a goal and two assists in a 12\u20139 loss to the [[Western Conference (NHL)|Western Conference]]. Heatley was selected for the [[56th National Hockey League All-Star Game|2008]] game, but had to withdraw due to a shoulder injury he suffered in an earlier game against the Detroit Red Wings.<ref name=\"Missed 2008 All-Star Game\">{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/news/story?id=3196467|title=Bruins' Savard chosen to replace injured Heatley in All-Star Game|accessdate=2008-04-25|publisher=ESPN|year=2008|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Heatley was selected to his fourth All-Star Game in 2009 and scored a goal in a 12\u201311 Eastern Conference win in a shootout.\n\n==International play==\n{{MedalTableTop| name = no}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{ih|CAN}} }}\n{{MedalSport | [[Ice hockey]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Ice hockey at the Olympic Games|Winter Olympics]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[Ice hockey at the 2010 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2010 Vancouver]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Ice Hockey World Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2003 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|2003 Finland]] |}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2004 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|2004 Czech Republic]] |}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2005 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|2005 Austria]] |}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2008 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|2008 Canada]] |}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2009 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|2009 Switzerland]] |}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[World Cup of Hockey|World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2004 World Cup of Hockey]] |}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IIHF World U20 Championship|World Junior Championships]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | [[World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2000 Sweden]] |}}\n{{MedalBronze | [[World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2001 Russia]] |}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n\nHeatley competed in two [[World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|World Junior Championships]] during his two-year career at the [[Wisconsin Badgers#Ice hockey|University of Wisconsin]]. His first, in [[2000 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2000]], ended with a bronze medal win against the US in a [[shootout (ice hockey)|shootout]]; Heatley scored a goal in the 4\u20133 victory.<ref>{{cite news|title=Czechs claim gold; Canada beats USA|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/hockey/wjc00/day9.htm|accessdate=2008-10-03|date=2000-01-04|newspaper=[[USA Today]]}}</ref> The next year, in [[2001 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2001]], Heatley scored three goals and five points as Canada won a second-straight bronze.\n\nHeatley made his senior international debut with [[Canada national men's ice hockey team|Team Canada]] at the [[2002 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|2002 World Championships]], after his rookie season with the [[Atlanta Thrashers]]. He scored four points as Canada was defeated in the quarter-finals by [[Slovakia national ice hockey team|Slovakia]]. The following year, Heatley led Team Canada in scoring (seven goals and ten points) at the [[2003 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|2003 World Championships]] in [[Finland]], en route to his first gold medal.\n\nHaving missed the [[Stanley Cup playoffs|playoffs]] once more with the Thrashers, Heatley participated in the [[2004 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|2004 World Championships]] in the [[Czech Republic]]. Heatley dominated with 11 points to lead all tournament scorers, earning his second-straight MVP award. Canada captured a second-straight gold medal, defeating [[Sweden national men's ice hockey team|Sweden]] 5\u20133 in the final. Heatley scored his eighth goal of the tournament in the third period, starting a rally from a 3\u20131 deficit.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canada beats Sweden for gold|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20040510&slug=worldhockey10|accessdate=2008-10-03|newspaper=Seattle Times|first=Erica|last=Bulman|date=2004-05-10}}</ref> Several months later, Heatley competed in the [[2004 World Cup of Hockey|2004 World Cup]] and contributed two assists as Canada defeated [[Finland national men's ice hockey team|Finland]] in the final to capture the second-ever [[World Cup of Hockey|World Cup]] championship.\n\nAt the [[2005 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|2005 World Championships]] in [[Austria]], his fourth-straight World Championships, Heatley did not achieve the same success, with seven points in nine games, as Canada was shut-out by the [[Czech Republic national ice hockey team|Czech Republic]] in the gold medal game.\n\nOn December 21, 2005, Heatley was chosen by Team Canada to participate in the [[Ice hockey at the 2006 Winter Olympics|2006 Winter Olympics]] in [[Turin]] \u2013 his first Olympic games.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dany Heatley: hard road to Turin |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/olympics-winter/dany-heatley-hard-road-to-turin-1.609074 |accessdate=2018-01-22 |publisher=CBC }}</ref> Heatley managed three points in six games as Canada, defending its [[Ice hockey at the 2002 Winter Olympics|2002]] gold medal, was eliminated in the quarter-finals by [[Russia men's national ice hockey team|Russia]].\n\nAs Heatley returned to the World Championships after a three-year absence in [[2008 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|2008]] \u2013 he was added to the roster with teammate [[Jason Spezza]] after the [[Ottawa Senators]] were eliminated from the playoffs \u2013 he became Team Canada's all-time goal-scorer<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5jnMmAkWM7B0KDudjonVDTzSneJcg \n |title=Heatley scores three as Canada dominates Slovenia 5-1 \n |date=2008-05-02 \n |accessdate=2008-05-06 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005225619/http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5jnMmAkWM7B0KDudjonVDTzSneJcg \n |archivedate=2012-10-05 \n |df= \n}}</ref> and then all-time point leader for the World Championships,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hockeycanada.ca/index.cfm/ci_id/55309/la_id/1.htm|\ntitle=Hockey Canada: Heatley moves past Yzerman to become all-time points leader for Canada\n|date=2008-05-04\n|accessdate=2008-05-06}}</ref> passing [[Marcel Dionne]] and [[Steve Yzerman]], accordingly.  Heatley finished the tournament with a staggering 12 goals and eight assists in nine games, however, Canada was defeated by Russia in overtime of the gold medal game.  Heatley was given MVP, Best Forward and All-Star Team honours.\n\nIn the summer of 2009, Heatley was invited to Team Canada's Olympic tryout camp in [[Calgary]], where he was booed on the ice by fans. On December 30, 2009, Heatley was selected to play for Team Canada at the 2010 Winter Olympics.\n<ref>{{Cite news|title=Canadian Olympic Hockey Team: 2010 Roster Released|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/12/30/canadian-olympic-hockey-t_n_407458.html|accessdate=2009-12-30|work=The Huffington Post|first=Craig|last=Kanalley|date=2009-12-30}}</ref>  Heatley helped lead Team Canada to an 8\u20130 win in the first game of the 2010 Olympic tournament by scoring two goals.<ref>{{cite news | first = Curtis | last = Zupke | title = Getzlaf, Perry score in Canada's 8-0 victory | url = http://olympics.freedomblogging.com/2010/02/16/getzlaf-perry-score-in-canadas-8-0-victory/3881/ | newspaper = [[Orange County Register]] | date = 2010-02-16 | accessdate = 2010-02-16 | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100219110140/http://olympics.freedomblogging.com/2010/02/16/getzlaf-perry-score-in-canadas-8-0-victory/3881/ | archivedate = 2010-02-19 }}</ref> On February 28, 2010, the team defeated the United States to win Canada's eighth gold medal in Olympic men's hockey.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Hockey remains Canada's game |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/hockey-remains-canada-s-game-1.936653|date=2010-03-01|accessdate=2018-01-23|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC Sports]]|author=The Canadian Press}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n===Citizenship===\nDany Heatley holds dual Canadian-German citizenship because his mother is German.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.badische-zeitung.de/sport/transfercoup-nuernberg-ice-tigers-angeln-sich-dany-heatley--111596088.html | title = Transfer Coup: Dany Heatley in DEL with Thomas Sabo | website = badische-zeitung.de | date = 2015-09-16 | accessdate = 2015-09-16 | language = German}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.idowa.de/home/artikel/2015/09/17/ice-tigers-holen-nhl-star-dany-heatley-eine-der-groessten-verpflichtungen.html | title = Ice Tigers sign NHL star Dany Heatley | website = idowa.de | date = 2015-09-17 | accessdate = 2015-09-17 | language = German }}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Car accident===\nOn September 29, 2003, Heatley was seriously injured in a car accident after he lost control of the [[Ferrari 360 Modena]] he was driving on a curved road in a residential area of Atlanta. The car struck a wall, splitting in half and ejecting Heatley and his passenger, Atlanta Thrashers' teammate [[Dan Snyder (ice hockey)|Dan Snyder]]. Heatley suffered a broken jaw, a minor [[concussion]], a bruised lung and a bruised kidney, and he tore three ligaments in his right knee. Snyder was critically injured with a [[skull fracture]] and died in hospital of [[sepsis]] on October 5, 2003. Heatley pleaded guilty to second-degree [[vehicular homicide]], driving too fast for conditions, failure to maintain a lane and speeding. He admitted to consuming alcohol prior to the accident, but his [[blood-alcohol content]] tested below the legal limit. He was sentenced to three years [[probation]] and the judge ruled that any vehicle driven by Heatley could not have more than six cylinders nor surpass 70&nbsp;mph (112&nbsp;km/h).<ref>{{cite news | title = Felony charge dropped for Thrashers star's plea | url = http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/news/story?id=1984060 | publisher = ESPN | date = 2005-02-04 |work=ESPN | accessdate = 2008-12-04}}</ref>  Heatley avoided having to go to trial as part of a plea deal that dropped the first-degree charge of vehicular homicide.<ref name=trade>{{cite news|title=Thrashers trade Heatley to Senators for Hossa|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/24/sports/hockey/24hockey.html?sq=heatley&scp=10&pagewanted=all|accessdate=2008-09-29|date=2005-08-24|newspaper=New York Times | first=Jason | last=Diamos}}</ref> The Thrashers and the Atlanta community were largely supportive of Heatley, and Snyder's family told the judge and prosecutors that nothing would be gained by imprisoning him.<ref name=\"vancouversun.com\"/>\n\n===Lawsuit against agent===\nIn August 2012, it was revealed that Heatley had filed an $11 million lawsuit against his longtime agent and business adviser Stacey McAlpine, McAlpine's parents Gerald and Eugenia, and several companies. The suit, filed in the [[Calgary]] [[Court of Queen's Bench of Alberta]], alleges that the defendants lured Heatley into several [[real estate]] ventures across [[Canada]] and the [[United States]] with promises of huge returns that never materialized. It is also alleged that Stacey McAlpine made unauthorized withdrawals of more than $4 million from Heatley's bank accounts. The defendant companies named in court documents are Presidential Suites Inc., Waterfront Development Inc., McAlpine Sports Management Inc., and NSEM Management Inc.<ref>{{cite news| title = Minnesota Wild star Dany Heatley sues ex-agent, others for $11-million | url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/hockey/dany-heatley-sues-ex-agent-others-for-11-million/article4487673/ | newspaper = [[The Globe and Mail]] | date = 2012-08-13 | accessdate = 2012-08-13}}</ref>\n\nOne month later, it was revealed that Heatley's former Senators teammate [[Chris Phillips]] was also initiating a $7.5 million suit against Stacey McAlpine to recover lost money as a result of bad real estate deals.<ref>{{cite web| title= Phillips joins Heatley, suing former agent | url=  http://ottawasun.com/2012/09/13/phillips-joins-heatley-suing-former-agent/wcm/9d16b861-6c9d-4ca6-8164-ebccd4605ebe | work=Ottawa Sun | date= 2012-09-13 | accessdate= 2018-01-23}}</ref> The suit, launched at the Ontario court in Ottawa, alleges Phillips felt he was misled by McAlpine and has not been able to recover monies invested.\n\nAfter a lengthy court process, Heatley was awarded $6.5 million from a judge in [[Calgary, Alberta]] on July 21, 2017.<ref>{{cite news| url = https://sports.yahoo.com/dany-heatley-wins-6-5-million-suing-former-agent-143505718.html | title = Dany Heatley wins $6.5 million suing former agent | work = [[Yahoo! Sports]] | date = 2017-07-21 | accessdate = 2017-07-21}}</ref> McAlpine was later arrested and charged with fraud, money laundering and theft by authorities in [[Winnipeg]], Manitoba, Canada, on October 18, 2017.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/nhl-player-agent-arrested-winnipeg-jets-police-1.4360286 | title = NHL player agent accused of defrauding Dany Heatley, Chris Phillips of $12 million | publisher = [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] | date = 2017-10-18 | accessdate = 2017-10-18}}</ref> McAlpine died on March 5, 2018, at the age of 54<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.passages.winnipegfreepress.com/passage-details/id-253719/MCALPINE_STACEY| title = Winnipeg Free Press PASSAGES | publisher = [[Winnipeg Free Press]] | date = 2018-03-05}}</ref>, and the charges of fraud, theft and laundering the proceeds of crime were stayed two days later.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/hockey/charges-stayed-against-late-former-nhl-palyer-stacey-don-mcalpine/article38281151/| title = Charges stayed against late former NHL player Stacey Don McAlpine | publisher = [[The Globe and Mail]] | date = 2018-03-13}}</ref>\n\n===Endorsements===\nHeatley was selected as the cover player for the 2004 instalment of the [[EA Sports]] [[NHL series|NHL video game]] franchise in 2003 ([[NHL 2004]]). However, due to the fallout from Heatley's crash shortly afterwards, EA switched the cover photo to [[Joe Sakic]],<ref>{{cite web |title=EA Sports Replaces Heatley With Sakic On \"NHL 2004\" Cover |url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/2003/12/02/Sponsorships-Advertising-Marketing/EA-Sports-Replaces-Heatley-With-Sakic-On-NHL-2004-Cover.aspx |website=sportsbusinessdaily.com |accessdate=July 12, 2018 |date=December 2, 2003}}</ref> although many copies of the game were shipped with his photo on them.\n\n===Records and milestones===\n'''NHL'''\n*All-Star Game record for most goals in a game (4, tied)\n*All-Star Skills Competition record for shooting accuracy (2004) \u2013 4 for 4 <small>(shared with [[Ray Bourque]], [[Mark Messier]], [[Tom\u00e1\u0161 Kaberle|Tomas Kaberle]], [[Evgeni Malkin]] and [[Jeremy Roenick]])</small>\n*First NHL game-winning shootout goal\n\n'''Team'''\n*[[List of Atlanta Thrashers records|Atlanta Thrashers franchise record]] for most points by a rookie (67)\n*[[Ottawa Senators records|Ottawa Senators franchise record]] for most goals in a season (50)\n*Ottawa Senators franchise record for most points in a season (105)\n*Ottawa Senators franchise record for longest point-scoring streak (22 games)\n*Ottawa Senators franchise record for most points in one post-season (22, tied with [[Jason Spezza]] and [[Daniel Alfredsson]])\n*First Ottawa Senator in franchise history to score 50 goals in a season\n*First Ottawa Senator in franchise history to score back to back 50 goal seasons\n\n'''International'''\n*[[Canada national men's ice hockey team|Team Canada]]'s all-time leading goal-scorer \u2013 42 (as of [[2010 Winter Olympics]])\n*Team Canada's all-time leading point-scorer \u2013 69 (as of 2010 Winter Olympics)\n\n==Career statistics==\n<!-- AS PER WIKIPEDIA STANDARD PLEASE DO NOT ADD STATS TILL END OF SEASON -->\n\n===Regular season and playoffs===\n<small>'''Bold''' indicates led league</small>\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! colspan=\"5\" | Regular&nbsp;season\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! colspan=\"5\" | Playoffs\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! Season\n! Team\n! League\n! GP\n! [[Goal (ice hockey)|G]]\n! [[Assist (ice hockey)|A]]\n! [[Point (ice hockey)|Pts]]\n! [[Penalty (ice hockey)|PIM]]\n! GP\n! G\n! A\n! Pts\n! PIM\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[1999\u20132000 NCAA Division I men's ice hockey season|1999\u201300]]\n| [[Wisconsin Badgers men's ice hockey|Wisconsin Badgers]]\n| [[Western Collegiate Hockey Association|WCHA]]\n| 38\n| 28\n| 28\n| 56\n| 32\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"\n| [[2000\u201301 NCAA Division I men's ice hockey season|2000\u201301]]\n| Wisconsin Badgers\n| WCHA\n| 39\n| 24\n| 33\n| 57\n| 74\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[2001\u201302 NHL season|2001\u201302]]\n| [[Atlanta Thrashers]]\n| [[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n| 82\n| 26\n| 41\n| 67\n| 56\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"\n| [[2002\u201303 NHL season|2002\u201303]]\n| Atlanta Thrashers\n| NHL\n| 77\n| 41\n| 48\n| 89\n| 58\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[2003\u201304 NHL season|2003\u201304]]\n| Atlanta Thrashers\n| NHL\n| 31\n| 13\n| 12\n| 25\n| 18\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"\n| 2004\u201305\n| [[SC Bern]]\n| [[National League A|NLA]]\n| 16\n| 14\n| 10\n| 24\n| 58\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| 2004\u201305\n| [[Ak Bars Kazan]]\n| [[Russian Hockey Super League|RSL]]\n| 11\n| 3\n| 1\n| 4\n| 22\n| 4\n| 2\n| 1\n| 3\n| 4\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"\n| [[2005\u201306 NHL season|2005\u201306]]\n| [[Ottawa Senators]]\n| NHL\n| 82\n| 50\n| 53\n| 103\n| 86\n| 10\n| 3\n| 9\n| 12\n| 11\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[2006\u201307 NHL season|2006\u201307]]\n| Ottawa Senators\n| NHL\n| 82\n| 50\n| 55\n| 105\n| 74\n| 20  \n| 7\n| '''15'''\n| '''22'''\n| 12\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"\n| [[2007\u201308 NHL season|2007\u201308]]\n| Ottawa Senators\n| NHL\n| 71\n| 41\n| 41\n| 82\n| 76\n| 4\n| 0\n| 1\n| 1\n| 6\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[2008\u201309 NHL season|2008\u201309]]\n| Ottawa Senators\n| NHL\n| 82\n| 39\n| 33\n| 72\n| 88\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"\n| [[2009\u201310 NHL season|2009\u201310]]\n| [[San Jose Sharks]]\n| NHL\n| 82\n| 39\n| 43\n| 82\n| 54\n| 14\n| 2\n| 11\n| 13\n| 16\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[2010\u201311 NHL season|2010\u201311]]\n| San Jose Sharks\n| NHL\n| 80\n| 26\n| 38\n| 64\n| 56\n| 18\n| 3\n| 6\n| 9\n| 12\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"\n| [[2011\u201312 NHL season|2011\u201312]]\n| [[Minnesota Wild]]\n| NHL\n| 82\n| 24\n| 29\n| 53\n| 28\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[2012\u201313 NHL season|2012\u201313]]\n| Minnesota Wild\n| NHL\n| 36\n| 11\n| 10\n| 21\n| 8\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"\n| [[2013\u201314 